WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.599
The models talk about proteins — but what do they actually look

2
00:00:03.699 --> 00:00:07.475
like? Let's trace two of them, atom by atom, from real structures.

3
00:00:08.166 --> 00:00:10.925
This is carbonic anhydrase — the enzyme we bolt

4
00:00:11.025 --> 00:00:14.088
onto the cell to turn carbon dioxide into carbonate.

5
00:00:14.188 --> 00:00:16.582
Every twist is its real, folded backbone.

6
00:00:16.966 --> 00:00:19.851
Follow the chain to where the chemistry happens: three

7
00:00:19.951 --> 00:00:22.726
histidines clamp a single zinc ion. That tiny pocket

8
00:00:22.826 --> 00:00:25.434
is what speeds the reaction about a million-fold.

9
00:00:27.866 --> 00:00:30.404
And this is the other one — the synthase that

10
00:00:30.504 --> 00:00:34.683
stitches glutamate into long gamma-P-G-A chains. This fold is AlphaFold's

11
00:00:34.783 --> 00:00:37.614
prediction, not a crystal, so we flag it honestly.

12
00:00:38.333 --> 00:00:41.365
Two real enzymes, two real shapes — and the pocket on each

13
00:00:41.465 --> 00:00:44.659
one is where every downstream number in this toolkit is born.

